<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=+2>INTRODUCTION</FONT></B></CENTER>

<CENTER>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></CENTER>

<CENTER>&nbsp;</CENTER>

<UL>
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Current technological advances will result in a complex distributed
multimedia computing infrastracture (like this:
<a href="c10afig/f10-1.JPG">fig. 10-1</a>)
</FONT></LI>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Interactive nature of multimedia applications requires that
the user be able to control the content of multimedia streams</FONT></LI>

<BR><FONT SIZE=+1>&nbsp;</FONT>
<BR><FONT SIZE=+1>But: most multimedia applications are stored in some
kind of storage server</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1>So: the performance of such applications depends directly
on the performance of storage servers</FONT>
<BR><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>&nbsp;
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Requirements of Multimedia-On-Demand Servers</FONT></LI>

<UL>
<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>real-time nature of multimedia data requires QoS quarantees.
</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>should be able to handle a big number of different types of
storage
devices constracted in a hierarchical fashion</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>must support thousands of concurrent clients
independently</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>the architecture should be scalable</FONT></LI>

<LI>
<FONT SIZE=+1>caching: the required data can be found in remote locations
</FONT></LI>
</UL>
<FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>&nbsp;
<BR><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT>&nbsp;</UL>

